metadata.name: monopole #44
metadata.description:
Physics is, above all, beautiful.

Inspired by all the things I find beautiful in physics, and the nostalgia I feel for my undergraduate days of learning about the universe. I sought here to explore what can be created with simple graphics showing simple physical systems. 

The vector field shown is the field from a collection of monopoles, such as electrons and positrons or hypothetical magnetic monopoles.

The papers and inks available are those I have on my desk.

A 2400x2400 download of the image can be generated by pressing UP, but this will take several minutes. An SVG download can be made by pressing DOWN and is suitable for plotting (or laser cutting).

metadata.name: sandspiral II #141
metadata.description: This is a re-imagining of my new forms 04: sand spirals mint from hic et nunc in April '21. (https://hen.hicathon.xyz/objkt/68268 ). It has been altered to produce unique mints. There are 12 different random traits seeded from the operation hash, but only four are visible: primary hue, secondary hue, initial rotation, and line width. All values are equal likelihood, so there is no "rarity" per se; aesthetic value is the only trait that matters.

metadata.name: Inertia #615
metadata.description:
This project will be reserved and free for 48 hours, for all the holders of any of my projects!

The amount of reserves for each user will be equal to the amount of all the token held at 13:00 CEST [UTC+2] (May 23)
(example: user holds 3 "Figment" and 2 "ACCUMULATOR", will be able to mint "Inertia" 5 times)

48h from now I will update the reserves list and burn the remaining tokens

WARINING: The reserves will expire 48h after the drop! And a price for the unlocked mintables will be set (unreserved mints will not be free).

---

"Inertia is a property of matter by which it continues in its existing state of rest or uniform motion in a straight line, unless that state is changed by an external force."

Particles are blasted from 2 to 4 sides of the canvas, each particle has its own mass and it has to traverse a friction-field, once it loses its momentum completely it stops and leaves a trace, adding or subtracting light from the canvas.

The friction-field has 18 possible mutation kinds.
Mutations are high-friction zones of various shapes.

Made just with JS on a canvas
right-click to save

metadata.name: rive #186
metadata.description:
Starting with a repeatable system of colors and/or triangles typically seen in geometric abstraction, rive employs generative art to break/split/rive those patterns–and the comfort we find in them–in slight, seemingly unintentional ways.  With each subsequent split, our comfort fades as the artwork is shredded into barely recognizable fragments of a once carefully orchestrated pattern.

Not all rivings are created equal; some are subtle and barely visible while others are acute and violent.  

What holds it together is what breaks it apart.  

created using triangles and p5js

rive
abstractment, 2022

___________________________

Functionality:
Press ‘p’ to save as a png.
Press 0-9 to render at varying degrees of quality. 0 to 9 (highest quality, ~15k x ~15k, depending on the dimensions).  The window background will change colors when completed rendering.
Press ⬆️ (arrow up) to increase pixel density by 0.5.
Press ⬇️ (arrow down) to decrease pixel density by 0.5.

metadata.name: Tympanic #65
metadata.description:
Tympanic is a companion piece to Euphonic [https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/10982] and is released as a free gift to all collectors of Euphonic.

Like Euphonic, this piece attempts to play with the idea of interference and emergent patterns, but this time does so by using pixelation instead of Moire. In this way, where Euphonic was about emergent melodies, Tympanic is about emergent rhythms.

This is built in WebGL 2 and so doesn't work in Safari 14 and below. All latest browsers will work as expected.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details.

metadata.name: 7VV1N5 #95
metadata.description:
GO BIG OR GO HOME.

After a week of minimalism code, our hero, the handsome artist Daniel, decided he needed something involving maximalism to reset the balance. Finding pairs to put together is satisfying.

Images will take 6-9 seconds to display and refresh between window resizing.

Use the z key or single click/tap to switch to "zoom" mode, which zooms in and fills the viewport; use z & tap/click to cycle through views. Use x and double-click/tap to go back to square mode.

Note: It doesn't work on Internet Explorer, because Microsoft. iOS is faster than Android.

-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

z, click, tap - Switch to & cycle "zoom" mode
x, double-click, double-tap - Switch back out of "zoom" mode.
h - Toggle high-res (slow)
s - Download and save image (takes a few seconds, longer for high-res)

metadata.name: Equilibrium #54
metadata.description: Equilibrium shows the algorithm in its search for balance in color and composition. It symbolizes how, at its core, generative art itself is the act of balancing constraints and freedom, consistency and variation, predictability and surprise. Based on empirical data, all mints should eventually converge to a stable state, though this is not guaranteed mathematically. Implemented in 5121 hand-crafted characters of JS code. Forever limited to 100 unique editions living on the Tezos blockchain. London - December 2021.
